Procedures

A procedure is a named snippet of text. They are typically defined with the \procedure pragma.

The name wrapped in double angled brackets is used as a shorthand way of transcluding the snippet. Each of these "procedure calls" can supply a different set of parameters:

This is the procedure, and the parameter is: Default value.

This is the procedure, and the parameter is: The parameter.

\procedure my-procedure(parameter:"Default value")
This is the procedure, and the parameter is: ''<<parameter>>''.
\end

A procedure is a named snippet of text. They are typically defined with the `\procedure` pragma.

The name wrapped in double angled <<.xL brackets Brackets>> is used as a shorthand way of <<.xL transcluding Transclusion>> the snippet. Each of these "procedure calls" can supply a different set of parameters:

--------

<<my-procedure>>
<<my-procedure "The parameter">>
Functions

A function is a named snippet of text containing a filter expression. Functions can have named parameters which are available within the function as variables.

Functions are usually defined with the \function pragma

2 * 1.5 = 3
6 * 1.5 = 9

\function my-function(parameter:"2")
[<parameter>multiply[1.5]]
\end

A function is a named snippet of text containing a filter expression. Functions can have named parameters which are available within the function as variables.

Functions are usually defined with the `\function` pragma

-------------

2 * 1.5 = <<my-function>><br>
6 * 1.5 = <<my-function 6>>
Macros
Macro Definition

Macro definitions are invisible. They are used in the examples below.

<!-- Can be defined in 1 line for short macros -->
\define sayhi(name:"Bugs Bunny") Hi, I'm <$text text=<<__name__>>/> 

<!-- Can be defined in several lines for longer macros -->
\define sayhi(name:"Bugs Bunny") 
Hi, I'm <$text text=<<__name__>>/> 
\end

Macro definitions are invisible.
They are used in the examples below.

Transclusions

You can incorporate the content of one tiddler within another using the Transclusion notation:

  • {{MyTiddler}} transcludes the content of a single tiddler
  • {{MyTiddler||TemplateTitle}} displays the tiddler through a specified TemplateTiddler
  • {{||TemplateTitle}} displays the specified template tiddler without altering the currentTiddler variable

You can also use a TextReference instead of a tiddler title:

  • {{MyTiddler!!field}} transcludes a specified field of a tiddler
  • {{!!field}} transcludes a specified field of the current tiddler
  • {{MyTiddler##index}} transcludes a specified indexed property of a DataTiddlers
  • {{##index}} transcludes a specified indexed property of the current DataTiddlers

The $:/Cheatsheet Transclusion tiddler on the left side is transcluded into the table using the transclusion-widget

{{$:/Cheatsheet Transclusion}}

Widgets
Basic Widgets

Widgets provide rich functionality within WikiText. They have the same syntax as HTML elements, but the tag name always starts with $. For example:

Widgets provide rich functionality within WikiText. They have the same syntax as HTML elements, but the tag name always starts with `$`. For example:

<$button message="tm-navigate" to="$:/Cheatsheet Widget">Open tiddler: ~$:/Cheatsheet Widget</$button>
Custom Widgets

Custom widget is a special kind of procedure that can be called using the same syntax as widgets.

Custom widgets can also be used to override built-in JavaScript widgets to customise their behaviour.

Custom widgets are usually defined with the pragma: \widget:

This is text from the widget, and the attribute is: xxxx

\widget $my.widget(attribute:"Default value")
---
This is text from the widget, and the attribute is: ''<<attribute>>''
\end

Custom widget is a special kind of <<.xL procedure Procedures>> that can be called using the same syntax as widgets.

Custom widgets can also be used to override built-in ~JavaScript widgets to customise their behaviour.

Custom widgets are usually defined with the pragma: `\widget`:

<$my.widget attribute="xxxx"/>
Variables

Variables can be defined with macro definitions, or the widgets <$set ...>, <$vars ...> or <$let ...>. For new code use the let-widget, because it is the latest.

This example uses the set-widget so the cheat sheet can also be used with old wikis.

For example:

To avoid the automatic wiki-link conversion for $:/Cheatsheet you can set tv-wikilinks="no":

Variables can be defined with [[macro definitions|$:/Cheatsheet MDefinition]], or the widgets `<$set ...>`, `<$vars ...>` or `<$let ...>`. For ''new code'' use the ''let-widget'', because it is the latest. 

This example uses the set-widget so the cheat sheet can also be used with old wikis.

For example:

<$set name="targetTiddler" value="$:/Cheatsheet Variable">
  <$button message="tm-navigate" to=<<targetTiddler>> >Open tiddler: <<targetTiddler>></$button>
</$set>

To avoid the automatic wiki-link conversion for `$:/Cheatsheet` you can set `tv-wikilinks="no"`:

<$let targetTiddler="$:/Cheatsheet Variable" tv-wikilinks="no">
  <$button message="tm-navigate" to=<<targetTiddler>> >Open tiddler: <<targetTiddler>></$button>
</$let>
Parser Modes

In order to display Tiddlers (usually the text field), the WikiText parser reads and interprets the content and applies WikiText rules. The parser has three modes:

  • pragma mode - the parser will recognise only "pragma" punctuation. eg: \import
  • block mode - the parser will recognise only "block" punctuation. eg: ! heading
  • inline mode - the parser will recognise only "inline" WikiText. eg: ''bold''
Pragmas

A pragma is a special component of WikiText that provides control over the way the remaining text is parsed.

Pragmas occupy lines that start with \. The following pragmas are available:

  • Pragma: \procedure – is used to define procedures
  • Pragma: \function – is used to define functions
  • Pragma: \widget – is used to define custom widgets
  • Pragma: \parameters – is used within procedure and widget definitions to declare the parameters that are expected, and their default values
  • Pragma: \whitespace – determines how spaces and newlines are treated within wikitext
  • Pragma: \import – is used to import definitions from other tiddlers that are identified with a filter
  • Pragma: \rules – adjusts the set of parser rules used to parse the remaining text
  • Pragma: \define – is used to define macros. It is a shortcut syntax for the SetVariableWidget
